+# AAI-CP3 — Software-agent actorship and sponsor-bound authority v0.1
+
+Status: CONTROLLED_PROMOTION_APPLIED  
+Date: 2026-05-16  
+Change class: accepted RFC extension + active machine-contract promotion + implementation/conformance support
+
+## Scope
+
+CP3 promotes a narrow authority identity/envelope layer for software agents.
+
+It makes the following explicit:
+
+- software-agent profile and instance are governed identities, not authority grants;
+- sponsor binding creates accountability, not blanket delegation;
+- model/tool/profile/session/credential identity is not authority;
+- agent authority must be action-class-specific, scoped, time-bounded, and revocation-aware;
+- agent authorization decisions must emit traces that explain allow/deny/human-approval outcomes.
+
+## Active-law changes
+
+CP3 adds one accepted RFC:
+
+- `02_accepted_rfcs/OFARM_Agent_Actorship_and_Authority_RFC_v0_1.md`
+
+CP3 promotes eight active machine contracts under `03_machine_contracts/schemas/authority/`.
+
+## What CP3 does not promote
+
+CP3 does not promote:
+
+- `AgentRunEnvelope`;
+- `AgentRunTrace`;
+- `AgentToolInvocationTrace`;
+- `AgentBlockedActionTrace`;
+- `AgentHandoffEnvelope`;
+- `AgentToolManifest`;
+- world-model runtime;
+- `EvidenceNeed`;
+- `ObservationRequest`;
+- runtime AI-agent readiness;
+- two-agent compatibility;
+- autonomous compliance decisioning;
+- production readiness;
+- external-standard readiness.
+
+## Deep Research use
+
+The attached Deep Research report is included as research context only. It supports the CP3 split-promotion posture: sponsor-bound actorship is mature enough to promote after revision, while world-model and request semantics remain experiment-first.
