+# CP3 disposition memo
+
+## Disposition
+
+Promote to active accepted RFC and active machine contracts.
+
+## Rationale
+
+CP3 closes the immediate authority identity gap needed after CP2. Public surfaces and result qualification can now ask, “which agent is acting, under whose sponsorship, under what scoped authority envelope, with what revocation posture, and what action-class posture?”
+
+## Controlled boundaries
+
+The promotion is intentionally narrow. It does not make agents autonomous governors and does not promote run/handoff semantics. It only gives OFARM a machine-checkable way to evaluate agent actorship and sponsor-bound authority.
+
+## Deep Research influence
+
+The research context recommended explicit `sponsor_id`, `executing_agent_id`, `actorship_basis`, and `authority_snapshot_ref`, with default no silent delegation. CP3 incorporates that recommendation without importing external protocol field names as baseline law.
+
+## Remaining risks
+
+- CP3 still needs CP4 for run/handoff tracing.
+- CP3 still needs CP5 for tool-manifest honesty.
+- CP3 still needs CP6 hostile runtime execution before runtime or two-agent readiness claims.
